Practical No 4
Aim: Configure routers in a network using Static routing protocol in Cisco
Packet Tracer and show transmission of packet from one network to another.
Theory:
Static routing is a routing technique in which routes are manually configured by the
network administrator. In static routing, the administrator specifies the destination
network and the next-hop IP address or exit interface to reach that network.
Devices Required
 Two Routers
 Two PCs
 Copper Straight-Through Cables
 Copper Cross-Over Cable
IP Addressing Table
Device Interface IP Address Subnet Mask
PC0 NIC 192.168.1.2 255.255.255.0
Router0 G0/0 192.168.1.1 255.255.255.0
Router0 G0/1 10.0.0.1 255.255.255.252
Router1 G0/0 10.0.0.2 255.255.255.252
Router1 G0/1 192.168.2.1 255.255.255.0
PC1 NIC 192.168.2.2 255.255.255.0
Procedure:
Step 1: Network Creation
1. Open Cisco Packet Tracer.
2. Place two routers and two PCs in the workspace.
3. Connect PC0 to Router0 using straight-through cable.
4. Connect Router0 to Router1 using cross-over cable.
5. Connect Router1 to PC1 using straight-through cable.
2
Step 2: PC Configuration
 Configure PC0 with IP address 192.168.1.2, subnet mask 255.255.255.0 and default
gateway 192.168.1.1.
 Configure PC1 with IP address 192.168.2.2, subnet mask 255.255.255.0 and default
gateway 192.168.2.1.
Step 3: Router Configuration
 Configure IP addresses on all router interfaces as per the IP addressing table.
 Enable all router interfaces.
 Configure static routes on both routers to reach the remote networks.
Result:-
Conclusion: Static routing was successfully configured on the routers and communication
between different networks was achieved.
